<chapter id="ch0075">
    <title>CURVED AND SPIRAL-SHAPED GRAM-NEGATIVE RODS</title>
    <sect1 id="ch0075s10000">
      <title>CURVED AND SPIRAL-SHAPED GRAM-NEGATIVE RODS</title>
      <sect2 id="ch0075s10001">
        <title>58 Algorithms for Identification of Curved and Spiral-Shaped Gram-Negative Rods</title>
        <anchor id="ch0075s10001a0001"/>
        <anchor id="ch0075s0000a0001"/>
        <para role="chapterAuthor"><phrase role="center">IRVING NACHAMKIN</phrase>
        </para>
        <para id="ch0075s0000p0001">Curved and spiral-shaped bacteria have a common microscopic morphology but represent diverse bacterial pathogens. These organisms are curved, helical, or spiral-shaped Gram-negative rods. Specific detection of these organisms may require a combination of tests, including microscopy, histologic staining of tissue, biochemical tests, antigen tests, serologic tests, bacteriologic culture, and molecular diagnostics.</para>
        <para id="ch0075s0000p0002">Most bacteria in this group of organisms are isolated from patients with gastrointestinal tract-related infections, but may be isolated from blood cultures, wound cultures, or other less common specimen types (<anchor id="ch0075s0000a0002"/><link linkend="ch0075s0000a0007">Table 1</link>). <emphasis>Campylobacter jejuni</emphasis> subsp. <emphasis>jejuni</emphasis> is the most frequently isolated curved Gram-negative rod associated with diarrheal illness, but with proper culture conditions, other <emphasis>Campylobacter, Helicobacter, Arcobacter</emphasis>, and <emphasis>Vibrio</emphasis> species may be detected in routine stool cultures. <emphasis>Helicobacter cinaedi</emphasis> and <emphasis>Helicobacter fennelliae</emphasis> are two important <emphasis>Helicobacter</emphasis> species isolated from fecal specimens (see <ulink url="ch0077#ch0077s0001">chapter 60</ulink>, “<emphasis>Helicobacter</emphasis>,” in this <emphasis>Manual</emphasis>). <emphasis>Helicobacter pylori</emphasis> is the most common curved Gram-negative rod isolated from gastric tissue, but other <emphasis>Helicobacter</emphasis> species have also been reported at this site. Increased hydrogen levels in the microaerobic environment are important for isolation of some <emphasis>Campylobacter</emphasis> and <emphasis>Helicobacter</emphasis> species. Of note, <emphasis>Campylobacter</emphasis> and <emphasis>Vibrio</emphasis> species are more frequently detected directly from fecal samples by using nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT) systems without the need for routine culture methods (see <ulink url="ch0061#ch0061s0001">chapters 44</ulink> and <ulink url="ch0076#ch0076s0001">59</ulink> of this <emphasis>Manual</emphasis>).</para>
        <para id="ch0075s0000p0003">Other less commonly isolated curved Gram-negative rods include the anaerobes<emphasis>Desulfovibrio</emphasis> spp., <emphasis>Sutterella wadsworthensis, Wolinella succinogenes</emphasis>, and <emphasis>Anaerobiospirillum</emphasis> spp., which may be isolated from fecal, blood, abscess material, or other clinical samples (<link linkend="ch0075s0000a0007">Table 1</link>). Several oxidase-positive nonfermenters, including <emphasis>Herbaspirillum</emphasis> species (see <ulink url="ch0063#ch0063s0001">chapter 46</ulink>), may also have a curved appearance.</para>
        <para id="ch0075s0000p0004">The spirochetes<emphasis>Borrelia</emphasis> spp. (see <ulink url="ch0079#ch0079s0001">chapter 62</ulink>) and <emphasis>Leptospira</emphasis> spp. (see <ulink url="ch0078#ch0078s0001">chapter 61</ulink>) cause systemic infections and are infrequently isolated in clinical microbiology laboratories, usually only with specialized media. These bacteria are strictly aerobic, and their optimal growth temperatures are from 28 to 30°C (<emphasis>Leptospira</emphasis> spp.) and 30 to 33°C (<emphasis>Borrelia</emphasis> spp.). <emphasis>Treponema</emphasis> spp. (see <ulink url="ch0080#ch0080s0001">chapter 63</ulink>) of clinical importance are diagnosed based on clinical and epidemiologic findings, as well as microscopic, serologic, and molecular test procedures.</para>
        <para id="ch0075s0000p0005">Many clinical laboratories, if not most, now use rapid identification systems such as matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization–time of flight mass spectrometry (MALDI-TOF) for quick identification of bacterial agents isolated in primary culture, or use multiplex molecular amplification systems for direct detection of common enteric pathogens in fecal samples. Given this, few laboratories perform conventional biochemical identification of the organisms described in this chapter. However, a simple flowchart for identification from fecal cultures is shown in<anchor id="ch0075s0000a0003"/><link linkend="ch0075s0000a0014">Fig. 1</link>.</para>
